# Typography and Interactive Components Rules

## 1. Font-size Variables and Typography

### Typography Token Declaration
- Font-size variables are declared in the Design System
- Respect Figma structure and nomenclature
- Apply same name transformation rules (`/` → `-`)

Do not use:
- Arbitrary text sizes
- Standard Tailwind values when a DS token exists

### Typography Consumption
Must always be done through:
- Tailwind utilities linked to DS
- Base `<Text>` component with respective variant and HTML element type
  - If it's a `<p>`, no need to specify — it's the default render

Avoid:
- Inline HTML text elements instead of the `Text` component
- Overriding variant values via `className` or `style` — except when Figma explicitly declares otherwise

---

## 2. Buttons and Standard Tailwind Usage

### 2.1 Physical Button Sizes
Height, width, and padding are not mandatory DS tokens — standard Tailwind values are allowed and recommended.
Applies to: horizontal padding, vertical padding, internal gaps.

### 2.2 Variant Categorization (CVA Structure)

Button component uses `cva` with variants:
- **`size`**
- **`variant`** (corresponds to `hierarchy` in Figma)
- **`colorScheme`** (corresponds to `color` in Figma)
- **`widthMode`** (corresponds to `behavior` in Figma)

When chromatic property depends on a `variant` + `colorScheme` combination → use `compoundVariants`.
If a property is shared across all variants → define it directly in `colorScheme`.

### 2.3 Default Values (`defaultVariants`)
Must declare defaults in `cva`. Example:
```typescript
size: 'md'
variant: 'primary'
widthMode: 'fixed'
colorScheme: 'default'
```
These values may vary per project — analyze and define when creating the component.

### 2.4 Button Component Public API
Main exposed props: `variant`, `colorScheme`.
Component must allow declaring all variants (size, widthMode, etc.) even if rarely used.

### 2.5 States and colorScheme
Each `colorScheme` must cover all DS-defined states, at minimum:
- background
- main text color

Mandatory interactive states: `default`, `hover`, `active (pressed)`, `focus-visible`.

Do not omit states defined in DS.

---

## 3. Background and Text in Buttons

- Background colors: must declare all corresponding states
- Text colors: must declare all corresponding states, aligned with each button state
- Do not assume implicit values

Button must be completely deterministic from `variant` + `colorScheme`.

---

## 4. Text Component Rules

- Follows same structural principles as Button
- Uses DS tokens for typography
- Does not have interactive states by default (no hover, focus, active)

---

## 5. DS Component Rendering

### Default Rendering
`Text` component must be able to render: `"span"`, `"p"`, and `"h1"` through `"h6"` via an `"as"` prop with default value `"p"`.

### asChild Prop
Must support `asChild`. When present, use Radix `Slot` — the child element defines the final render.

Use cases: rendering buttons as links, custom wrappers, integration with other components.

`asChild` is mandatory for rendering buttons as links to maintain correct HTML semantics.

---

## 6. Link Usage

Navigation links: use exclusively `next/link`.

Do not create custom wrappers or alternative Link components.

When a button acts as a link → use `Button` + `asChild` + `Link` as child.

Common `<a>` anchors are only allowed for external links.

---

## 7. CVA Class Declaration

All classes defined in `cva` must be declared as inline strings directly within the cva configuration.

Not allowed: class arrays, `.join(" ")`, helpers to group classes, dynamic concatenations.

Allowed: explicit strings per variant.

---

## 8. Scope for Interactive Components

All interactive components added to DS must comply with the same rules defined for Button:
inputs, toggles, selects, tabs, custom controls, etc.

Each component:
- Can define different variant categories in `cva`
- Must have `defaultVariants`
- Must cover all states defined in DS
- Must be completely deterministic from its props

Do not: omit states, invent variants not in DS, or assume implicit styles.
